### Step[12]
Analysis: What has been done: 
- Preprocessing: loaded metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv and scoped to the incident window 2022-03-20 17:00–17:30 (UTC+8). Many metric/trace series have global P95 == 0 producing noisy flags; these were filtered where possible. Trace and log summaries were used to focus candidate services.
- Anomaly detection & metric analysis: computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi) using full series, then checked the incident window. Using a 1.5×P95 breach rule (and ignoring P95 == 0 artifacts) produced substantive breaches: a pronounced container_memory_failures spike on adservice-1 at 2022-03-20 17:05:00+08 (value 82.5, global P95 49.5), and short consecutive container_network_receive_MB spikes on cartservice-2 at 2022-03-20 17:12:00 and 17:13:00 (value ≈0.3477 MB vs p95≈0.1020), plus similar consecutive spikes on cartservice-0 at 17:19:00 and 17:20:00. Other candidate single-sample breaches (currency/checkout/shipping/mesh) were lower-severity.
- Trace analysis: traces filtered to candidate components confirmed non-zero traffic to adservice and cartservice, but most trace metrics had global P95 == 0 and were uninformative for additional localization. Traces did show row_count reaching adservice and cartservice during the window, supporting the metric relevance.
- Log analysis: log.row_count was non-zero for many services across the window, but log.error_count for adservice-1/adservice-2/cartservice-0/cartservice-2 was 0 in-window, so logs did not show explicit error_count spikes to further corroborate.

What can be derived: 
- There are two distinct, well-supported fault events in the window: (1) adservice-1 experienced repeated container_memory_failures with a clear large spike at 2022-03-20 17:05:00+08 (value 82.5 vs global P95 49.5). This meets the fault-identification criteria (substantive amplitude >> threshold and repeated). 
- (2) The next best-supported fault candidate is a short network-receive throughput spike on cartservice, with cartservice-2 showing consecutive breaches at 2022-03-20 17:12:00 and 17:13:00 (value ≈0.3477 MB with p95≈0.1020). Cartservice-0 had a separate pair of spikes later at 17:19–17:20. Given there are exactly two failures to localize in the specified window, the strongest pairing is: adservice-1 memory failure at 17:05 and cartservice-2 network spike at 17:12 (these are temporally distinct and both meet the anomaly/fault criteria). 

Caveats and reasoning: 
- Many series are zero-valued globally which reduces trace/log signal quality; we therefore prioritized metrics with P95 > 0 and breaches substantially above P95 (>=1.5×P95) and with consecutive samples to avoid single-sample noise. 
- log.error_count did not show non-zero entries for the implicated components, so the diagnosis relies mainly on metrics (memory_failures and network_receive_MB) and corroborating trace row_count showing traffic to those services. 

Therefore the most defensible identification of the two failures (given available telemetry and following the required workflow) are as below.
